\begin{abstract}
This note has several aims. Firstly, it portrays a {non-standard analysis}\ as a functor, namely a functor ${^\star}$ that maps any set $A$ to the set ${^\star} A$ of its {non-standard}\ elements. That functor, from the category of sets to itself, is postulated to be an equivalence on the full subcategory of finite sets onto itself and to preserve finite projective limits (equivalently, to preserve finite products and equalizers). Secondly, ``Local'' {non-standard analysis}\ is introduced as a structure which we call {lim-rim}, in particular exact {lim-rim} s. The interplay between these, and ultrafilters and ultrapowers, and also cardinality relations and notions depending on a cardinality such as saturation and what we call ``confinement'' and ``exactness'', are investigated.

In particular, one constructs {non-standard}\ analyses, with ``good'' kinds of {lim-rim}. In these one may say that ${^\star} A$ -- ``the adjunction of all possible limits from $A$'' -- plays a role analogous to that of the algebraic closure of a field -- ``the adjunction of all roots of polynomials''. Then in the same spirit as with the latter, one has uniqueness up to isomorphism, and also universality and homogeneity, provided one has enough General Continuum Hypothesis. The cardinality of ${^\star} A$ will be something like $2^{2^{|A|}}$ -- the same as that of the set of ultrafilters in $A$, and one has a high degree of saturation.

Also, one notes that the functor ${^\star}$ can be applied again to ${^\star} A$, giving ${^\star}{^\star} A$,
${^\star}{^\star}{^\star} A$, and so forth. In particular, we focus on the two different embeddings of ${^\star} A$ into ${^\star}{^\star} A$ and prove some of their properties, with some applications.
\end{abstract}

\maketitle

\tableofcontents

\setcounter{section}{-1}

This note is a sequel to the less formal \cite{Levy}. Here I make things more precise, clarify and develop them, and add some material about iterated {non-standard analysis}. In particular, a {non-standard analysis}\ (which here gives ``non-standard elements'' to any set) is approached as a functor (a connection between {non-standard analysis}\ and category theory was given in \cite{Saigo}). ``Local'' {non-standard analysis}\ is introduced as a structure which I call {lim-rim}, in particular exact {lim-rim} s. The interplay between these, and ultrafilters and ultrapowers, and also cardinality relations and notions depending on a cardinality such as saturation and what I call ``confinement'' and ``exactness'', are investigated.{\par\medskip}

In the second section, dedicated to iterated {non-standard analysis}, the two embeddings $\nu$ and ${^\star}\nu$ of ${^\star} A$ into ${^\star}{^\star} A$ are focused upon. These embeddings are highly distinct. In the last paragraph a simple criterion (Prop.\ \ref{Prop:nunustar}) that the values they take satisfy a given standard relation is given, which has some interesting consequences and applications.

\section{Notations}
Denote the cardinality of a set $A$ by $|A|$.
For a cardinality ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$, denote by ${\mathfrak{{m}}}^+$ the successor cardinality.
Denote the power set of a set $A$ (the set of all subsets of $A$) by ${\mathcal{P}} A$.

\section{{Non-Standard Analysis}}

\subsection{{Non-Standard Analysis}\ as a Functor}
\begin{Def}\label{Def:na}
Let ${\mathcal{S}}{\mathcal{E}}{\mathcal{T}}$ be the category of sets and maps between them, and let ${\mathcal{F}}{\mathcal{I}}{\mathcal{N}}$ be its
full subcategory of finite sets and maps between them.
A {{\em\bf}{non-standard analysis}} will be defined as a (covariant) functor ${^\star}:{\mathcal{S}}{\mathcal{E}}{\mathcal{T}}\to{\mathcal{S}}{\mathcal{E}}{\mathcal{T}}$ which (i) maps ${\mathcal{F}}{\mathcal{I}}{\mathcal{N}}$ to itself as a self-equivalence of ${\mathcal{F}}{\mathcal{I}}{\mathcal{N}}$; (ii) preserves finite projective limits.
\end{Def}

${^\star}$ of a set $A$ will be denoted by ${^\star} A$ and its elements will be referred to as the {{\em\bf}{non-standard}\ elements} of $A$ (thus, if $A$ is, say, the set of integers, then the elements of ${^\star} A$ will be called ${^\star}$integers). Similarly the image by ${^\star}$ of a map $f$ will be denoted by ${^\star} f$.{\par\medskip}

In particular, for every $a$ the set $\{a\}$ is a singleton, thus an object of ${\mathcal{F}}{\mathcal{I}}{\mathcal{N}}$, and ${^\star}$ being an equivalence on ${\mathcal{F}}{\mathcal{I}}{\mathcal{N}}$, ${^\star}\{a\}$ is also a singleton and its sole element will be denoted by $\nu(a)$ ($\nu$ from ``new''). In many cases, we will tend to identify $a$ with $\nu(a)$ (see below).{\par\medskip}

As for condition (ii), it is equivalent to ${^\star}$ preserving finite products (equivalently products of two sets $A$ and $B$, being the projective limit of the diagram $A,B$ (no maps)\NOT{, characterized by the appropriate universal property}) and equalizers $\{c\in C|f_1(c)=f_2(c)\}$ of two maps $f_1,f_2:C\to D$, (i.e.\ the projective limit of the diagram $C{\to\atop\to}D$ -- the maps are $f_1$ and $f_2$\NOT{ -- characterized by the appropriate universal property}).{\par\medskip}

This means that the images by ${^\star}$ of the projections $A\times B\to A,\,A\times B\to B$ make ${^\star}(A\times B)$ the product ${^\star} A\times{^\star} B$; and if $E$ is the subset $\{c\in C\,|\,f_1(c)=f_2(c)\}$, i.e., with the inclusion map $E\to C$, the equalizer of $f_1$ and $f_2$, then ${^\star}$ of the inclusion map makes ${^\star} E$ the equalizer of ${^\star} f_1,{^\star} f_2:{^\star} C\to{^\star} D$. But since any subset of $C$ is an equalizer, this means that ${^\star}$ of any inclusion map $E\to C$ is injective, and can be viewed as an inclusion ${^\star} E\subset{^\star} C$, and in the above situation ${^\star} E=\{{^\star} c\in{^\star} C\,|\,{^\star} f_1({^\star} c)={^\star} f_2({^\star} c)\}$.{\par\medskip}

In particular, ${^\star}$ of the diagonal of $A\times A$ -- the equalizer of the two projections -- can serve as the diagonal of ${^\star} A\times{^\star} A$.{\par\medskip}

\begin{exm}\label{exm:na}

Of course, a trivial example for {non-standard analysis}\ is the identity functor, where ${{^\star}}A=A$ and all {non-standard}\ elements are, in fact, standard -- of the form $\nu(a)$.{\par\medskip}

To get a non-trivial example, Let $S$ be a fixed set of indices and ${\mathcal{U}}$ a fixed ultrafilter in $S$. For any set $A$ we have the {{\em\bf} ultrapower} $A_{\mathcal{U}}:=A^S/{\mathcal{U}}$, defined as the power $A^S$ modulo the equivalence relation: equality modulo ${\mathcal{U}}$.{\par\medskip}

We have here a covariant functor $A\mapsto A_{\mathcal{U}}$ (which depends on $S$ and ${\mathcal{U}}$)
from the category of sets to itself.  The image $f_{\mathcal{U}}$ by the functor of a map $f:A\to B$ between sets will map $[\xi]\in A_{\mathcal{U}}$, where $\xi:S\to A$, to $[f\circ\xi]\in B_{\mathcal{U}}$.{\par\medskip}

This ultrapower functor satisfies (i) and (ii) of Definition \ref{Def:na}. Indeed, (i) is immediate, because if $F$ is finite then for any $\xi:S\to F$ there is a unique $a\in F$ such that $\xi^{-1}(\{a\})\in{\mathcal{U}}$, and then $\xi$ is, modulo ${\mathcal{U}}$, the constant $a$. As for (ii), this functor preserves finite products - $(A\times B)_{\mathcal{U}}$ is identified with
$A_{\mathcal{U}}\times B_{\mathcal{U}}$ in an obvious manner, and if $f_1,f_2:C\to D$, and
$E=\{c\in C\,|\,f_1(c)=f_2(c)\}$ is the equalizer, then the equalizer of $(f_1)_{\mathcal{U}},(f_2)_{\mathcal{U}}:C_{\mathcal{U}}\to D_{\mathcal{U}}$ is
\begin{eqnarray*}
&&\{[\xi]\in C_{\mathcal{U}}\,|\,(f_1)_{\mathcal{U}}([\xi])=(f_2)_{\mathcal{U}}([\xi])\}=\\
&&=\{[\xi]\in C_{\mathcal{U}}\,|\,[f_1\circ\xi]=[f_2\circ\xi]\}=\\
&&=\{[\xi]\in C_{\mathcal{U}}\,|\,\exists U\in{\mathcal{U}},\,\,(f_1\circ\xi)|_U=(f_2\circ\xi)|_U\}=\\
&&=\{[\xi]\in C_{\mathcal{U}}\,|\,\exists U\in{\mathcal{U}}\,\,\xi(U)\subset E\}=\\
&&=\{[\xi]\in C_{\mathcal{U}}\,|\,\exists\eta:S\to E\,\,[\xi]=[\eta]\},
\end{eqnarray*}
which is identified with $E_{\mathcal{U}}$.\qed{\par\medskip}

This means that taking ${^\star} A:=$ the ultrapower $A_{\mathcal{U}}$, gives us a {non-standard analysis}, {as per Definition \ref{Def:na}}.{\par\medskip}
\end{exm}

\subsection{{Non-Standard Analysis}\ as a Functor, continued}\label{S:NAFco}
If $A$ is a set and $a\in A$, there is an inclusion map $\{a\}\to A$, and its ${^\star}$ is an injection ${^\star}\{a\}\to{^\star} A$, i.e.\ $\{\nu(a)\}\to{^\star} A$, identifying $\nu(a)$ with an element of ${^\star} A$ (Consequently, if $A\ne\emptyset$ then ${^\star} A\ne\emptyset$) -- if $a$ belongs to some (standard) set -- has some property -- then $\nu(a)$ is one of the {non-standard}\ elements of the set -- has the ${^\star}$property. These $\nu(a)$'s, with $a\in A$, might be referred to as the {{\em\bf} standard elements} of $A$, but (if $A$ is infinite) $A$ may have other elements, not of the form $\nu(a)$,\,\,$a\in A$.{\par\medskip}

Similarly, $\nu(a_1,\ldots,a_n)$ is identified with $(\nu(a_1),\ldots,\nu(a_n))$, and if $a_1\,\ldots,a_n$ satisfy some relation $R\subset A_1\times\cdots\times A_n$ then $\nu(a_1),\ldots,\nu(a_n)$ satisfies ${^\star} R$.{\par\medskip}

We will sometimes loosely view any finite set $F$ as a set of a kind of {\em truth-values} and any map between finite sets $f:F_1\to F_2$ as a kind of {\em logical operation}, \`a la {\bf AND}, {\bf OR}, {\bf NOT}. Then the equivalence that ${^\star}$ induces on ${\mathcal{F}}{\mathcal{I}}{\mathcal{N}}$ is used as an identification for these truth-values and logical operations. Maps $f:A_1\times A_2\times\cdot\times A_n\to F$, where $A_i, i=1\ldots n$ are sets and $F$ is finite, are viewed as {\em predicates} on $A_1,A_2,\ldots,A_n$. Composing them with maps between finite sets defines a kind of {\em logical operations among predicates}. But the fact that ${^\star}$ preserves finite products and equalizers makes, e.g., a ${\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}^2$-valued predicate the same as a pair of ${\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$-valued predicates, and if $F'\subset F$ then $F'$-valued predicates embed into $F$-valued ones. Therefore the ${\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$-valued predicates determine all others, while applying ${^\star}$ to predicates commutes with all ``logical operations'', in other words, applying ${^\star}$ to ${\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$-valued predicates commutes with the propositional calculus operations {\bf AND}, {\bf OR}, {\bf NOT} etc.{\par\medskip}

As said above, we identify $\nu({\textbf{True}})={\textbf{True}}$,\,\,$\nu({\textbf{False}})={\textbf{False}}$.{\par\medskip}

For any ${\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$-valued predicate $f$, if $E$ is the subset of
$A_1\times A_2\times\cdots\times A_n$ where it holds, then $E$ is the equalizer of $f$ with the constant map $A_1\times A_2\times\cdots\times A_n\to{\textbf{True}}$, the latter being the composition of $\{{\textbf{True}}\}\to{\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$ with the sole map
