\subsection{Features of the Conventional Approach to {Non-Standard Analysis}}
{non-standard analysis}\ was constructed by its founder, Abraham Robinson
(\cite{Robinson}) as a {non-standard}\ model of part of Set Theory. In his and
following treatments (see several treatises in the bibliography)
\footnote{In another direction, beginning with E.~Nelson \cite{Nelson}, one
constructs a special Set Theory for {non-standard analysis}.}
the idea is to start with a ``big'' structure -- a set $V$, with the restriction to it of the membership relation $\in$, which will be big enough so that usual mathematics could be done in it (should contain, e.g.\ ${\mathbb{{N}}}$ (the natural numbers), ${\mathbb{{R}}}$ (the real numbers), sets of them, sets of these etc.) $V$ is to be provided with a ``mirror'' ``{non-standard}''
structure ${^\star} V$ with a relation ${{^\star}\!\!}\in$, viewed as an ``interpretation'' of the $\in$ of $V$ (Also, ``interpret'' ``$=$'' in $V$ by ``$=$'' in ${^\star} V$), so that

\begin{enumerate}
\item
$V$ is embedded in ${^\star} V$ -- identified with a subset of ${^\star} V$. The members of
$V$ (thus considered as members of ${^\star} V$) are referred to as {\em standard}
(yet by ``{non-standard}'' elements we mean any members of ${^\star} V$).

\item
A {\em Transfer Principle} holds: any (in some constructions one has to say:
``bounded'') first-order logical expression with members of $V$ as constants which is a true sentence when quantifiers are interpreted relative to $V$ will remain a true sentence if (the constants -- members of $V$ -- are replaced by their identified images in ${^\star} V$ and) $\in$ is replaced by ${{^\star}\!\!}\in$ and the quantifiers are interpreted relative to ${^\star} V$. In this sense ${^\star} V$ is a model to the true in $V$ sentences of the first-order theory with $\in$ and all elements of $V$ as constants.

\item
By Transfer, for any standard set $A$, a standard $a\in V$ will be an ${{^\star}\!\!}\in$-member of it if and only if it is a usual member, but in ${^\star} V$\,\,$A$ may have other, {\em{non-standard}} members. The set of all elements of ${^\star} V$ which ${{^\star}\!\!}\in$-belong to $A$ is denoted by ${^\star} A$. Again by Transfer, ${^\star} (A\times B)$ is canonically identified with ${^\star} A\times\,{^\star} B$, thus for relations, functions etc.\ we have the ${^\star}$-relation, ${^\star}$-function etc.\ among members of ${^\star} V$ (which for standard elements coincides with the original relation, function
etc.) When there is no danger of misunderstanding, one often uses the same
symbol (e.g.\ $+$, $<$) for the ${^\star}$-relation etc.\ as for the original.

\item
${^\star} V$ is indeed ``{non-standard}'' -- it contains elements not in $V$, and one has features, usually some kind of ``saturation'' (see below), which will ensure, say, that there is an ${^\star} n\in{^\star} V$ which ${{^\star}\!\!}\in$-belongs to the set ${\mathbb{{N}}}$ of natural numbers, but such that for every standard $m\in N$,\,\,$m\;{{^\star}\!\!}<{^\star} n$ (i.e.\ $(m,{^\star} n)$ ${{^\star}\!\!}\in$-belongs to the graph of $<$). Such ${^\star} n$'s are naturally referred to as
``infinite'' or ``unlimited''
\footnote{In fact, as in footnote \ref{f:i}, for ${\mathbb{{N}}}$ the existence of ``infinite'' members needs only the existence of some not standard members -- one easily proves using Transfer that all ${^\star}$-members of a finite standard $A$ are standard, hence any ${^\star}$-member of ${\mathbb{{N}}}$ which is not standard is automatically bigger than all standard
numbers.}
and by Transfer they have reciprocals in ${^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$, referred to as ``infinitesimal''.
\end{enumerate}

The ``philosophy'' here is to develop the theory from these properties, paying
less attention to the way such ${^\star} V$ is constructed (or proved to exist).
The usual construction is by an ultrapower or a modification of it.
Anyway, one has to have a set $V$ to make the construction, hence only
subsets of it will have {non-standard}\ members.
{\par\medskip}

\subsection{Ultrafilters of {Non-Standard}\ Elements}
Let us be given a {non-standard analysis}, {as per Definition \ref{Def:na}}. For any set $A$, and any
${^\star} x\in{^\star} A$, and for any $S\subset A$, we have ${^\star} S\subset{^\star} A$, thus either
${^\star} x\in{^\star} S$ or ${^\star} x$ is not in ${^\star} S$ $\Leftrightarrow$ it is in the complement
${{^\star}}A\setminus{^\star} S={^\star} (A\setminus S)$. Put otherwise: for any ${\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$-valued predicate
$f:A\to{\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$ we have ${^\star} f:{}{^\star} A\to{^\star}{\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}={\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$ and ${^\star} f({^\star} x)$ is either ${\textbf{True}}$ or ${\textbf{False}}$.{\par\medskip}

Hence any ${^\star} x\in{}{^\star} A$ induces a map ${\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}^A\to{\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$, which is easily seen to be a Boolean-algebra homomorphism, i.e.\ an ultrafilter in $A$.{\par\medskip}

In fact, we may replace ${\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$ by any other finite set $F$, and view the set ${\beta} A$ of the ultrafilters in $A$ as the set of natural mappings between the functor from ${\mathcal{F}}{\mathcal{I}}{\mathcal{N}}$ to ${\mathcal{S}}{\mathcal{E}}{\mathcal{T}}$\,\,$F\mapsto F^A={\text{Hom}}(A,F)$, and the inclusion functor ${\mathcal{F}}{\mathcal{I}}{\mathcal{N}}\to{\mathcal{S}}{\mathcal{E}}{\mathcal{T}}$.{\par\medskip}

Then to a ${^\star} x\in{^\star} A$ corresponds the ultrafilter: the mapping $[f\mapsto{^\star} f({^\star} x)]:{\text{Hom}}(A,F)\to F$. This is clearly a natural mapping between the functors $A\mapsto{^\star} A$ and $A\mapsto{\beta} A$.{\par\medskip}

Note, that although the functor $A\mapsto{\beta} A$ is a canonically defined functor on sets, which maps injections to injections, it does not preserve finite products (hence is not a {non-standard analysis}\ {as per Definition \ref{Def:na}}). The projections $A\times B\to A$ and $A\times B\to B$ define onto mappings ${\beta}(A\times B)\to{\beta} A$ and ${\beta}(A\times B)\to{\beta} B$, hence induce a ${\beta}(A\times B)\to{\beta} A\times{\beta} B$, which is also onto, but is usually not one-to-one. Thus this functor does not satisfy (ii) of Definition \ref{Def:na} (while it satisfies (i)).{\par\medskip}

One may view a {non-standard analysis}\ as a quest to extend sets by adjoining all (or some) possible limits. This in close analogy in spirit to extending a field to its algebraic closure by adjoining all possible roots of algebraic equations. In the latter case one would like to simply define the adjoined elements as labeled by the irreducible polynomial they satisfy, but that is hampered by such facts as the polynomial whose roots are the sums of the roots of two irreducible polynomials being not irreducible.
\footnote{Which may be viewed as the ``reason'' for the existence of several
conjugate roots: the polynomial $d(t)$ whose roots are the differences of the
roots of the irreducible $f(t)$ has a factor $t$ but also other irreducible
factors, testifying to differences $\ne0$.}
The algebraic closure thus contains conjugate elements with the same irreducible polynomial and for any such elements there is an automorphism of the algebraic closure exchanging them.{\par\medskip}

Similarly in our case we would like to label the adjoined ``{non-standard}\ elements'' by
the ultrafilters on the original set. After all, these ultrafilters (and ultrafilters in finite products of sets) give all the possible ways properties (and relations) can conceivably hold or not. But that would not work precisely because the functor ${\beta}$ does not preserve finite products. There is a naturally defined Cartesian product of filters, but the Cartesian product of two ultrafilters ${\mathcal{U}}\in{\beta} A,{\mathcal{V}}\in{\beta} B$ is in general not an ultrafilter -- it is the intersection of all ultrafilters in $A\times B$ that map to $({\mathcal{U}},{\mathcal{V}})$ in the above mapping ${\beta}(A\times B)\to{\beta} A\times{\beta} B$.{\par\medskip}

We too will have a construction (\S\ref{S:car}) where there will be ``conjugate'' {non-standard}\ elements with the same ultrafilter and any such conjugate elements will be exchangeable by an automorphism, provided one has enough General Continuum Hypothesis (GCH), and then, in the same spirit as with algebraic closures, one has uniqueness (for fixed ``basis'' $B$ -- see below) up to isomorphism, and also universality and homogeneity.
{\par\medskip}


\subsection{{Lim-Rim} s -- Local {Non-Standard Analysis}}
Given a {non-standard analysis}, one may focus on a particular set $B$ and try to extract what the {non-standard analysis}\ says about this $B$ (hence about its subsets).{\par\medskip}

The information telling which {non-standard}\ elements satisfy which relations is encoded in the ultrafilters on $B^I$,\,$I$ finite. The {non-standard analysis}\ gives us a natural mapping $({^\star} B)^I\to{\beta}(B^I)$ between these two (contravariant) functors on $I$ from ${\mathcal{F}}{\mathcal{I}}{\mathcal{N}}$ to ${\mathcal{S}}{\mathcal{E}}{\mathcal{T}}$. If for any set $I\in{\mathcal{S}}{\mathcal{E}}{\mathcal{T}}$ we will define ${\beta}_c(A^I)$ as the set of ultrafilters on the {\em cylinder Boolean algebra of $B^I$} (the members of the cylinder Boolean algebra are the subsets of $B^I$ that depend only on a finite number of coordinates. In case $I$ is finite this is just the power set of $B^I$), then any natural $({^\star} B)^I\to{\beta}(B^I)$ on the finite sets $I$ extends in a unique way to a natural $({^\star} B)^I\to{\beta}_c(B^I)$ on all sets $I$. Moreover, we can take $I={^\star} B$ itself and then the image by the natural mapping of any element of $({^\star} B)^I$ will be known if we know the image in ${\beta}_c\left( B^{{}{{^\star}}B}\right)$ of the identity family $\in({^\star} B)^{{^\star} B}$.

\begin{Def}
We say that a set $E$ has the structure of a {{\em\bf}{lim-rim}} over a set
\footnote{we shall usually have $B$ infinite.}
(basis) $B$ if either of the equivalent following is given. (i) An  ultrafilter ${\mathcal{L}}$ on the cylinder Boolean algebra of $B^E$, which will be referred to as the {{\em\bf} defining cylinder ultrafilter} of the {lim-rim}\ (then we shall also speak of the {lim-rim}\ $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$ over $B$). (ii) A natural mapping between the (contravariant) functors on sets $I$: $E^I$ and ${\beta}_c(B^I)$, where the latter denotes the set of ultrafilters in the cylinder Boolean algebra. It will be referred to as the {{\em\bf} defining natural mapping} of the {lim-rim}. (Note that these functors and the natural mapping are defined for any $I$, yet they are determined by giving them for the finite $I$.)
\end{Def}

Here, the defining cylinder ultrafilter ${\mathcal{L}}$ in $B^E$ can be recovered as the image, by the natural mapping, in ${\beta}_c\left( B^E\right)$, of the identity family in $E^E$. On the other hand, if ${\mathcal{L}}$ is given, what it does is deciding, for any (finite) family $\eta\in E^I$ indexed by a finite $I$ (pushing ${\mathcal{L}}$, using the map $B^E\to B^I$ induced by $\eta:I\to E$, to
an ultrafilter in $B^I$) whether relations -- subsets of $B^I$ -- hold or
not, thus transferring such $I$-relations in $B$ (= subsets of $B^I$) into
$I$-relations in $E$, as a {non-standard}\ setting should. This new $I$-relation in $E$ will be referred to as the {\em transfer} or ${^\star}$ of the original $I$-relation in $B$.{\par\medskip}

To put it otherwise: for an $n$-tuple $(e_1,\ldots,e_n)$ of elements of $E$, a
relation $R\subset B^n$\,\,${^\star}$-holds for $(e_1,\ldots,e_n)$ if and only if for $\psi\in B^E$,
$(\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})\in R$ holds modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$.{\par\medskip}

To conclude:{\par\medskip}

\begin{Prop}
Given a {non-standard analysis}\ {as per Definition \ref{Def:na}}, it induces on any set $B$ a {lim-rim}\ $E$ over $B$, where $E={^\star} B$.
\end{Prop}
And as said above, this {lim-rim}\ captures which relations about $B$, or its subsets, are satisfied by $n$-tuples of {non-standard}\ elements $e_1,\ldots,e_n$. We may say that a {lim-rim}\ $E$ over $B$ defines a ``local'' {non-standard analysis}, with $E$ the set of {non-standard}\ elements of $B$, completely satisfactory as a {non-standard analysis}\ as long as one restricts oneself only to $B$ or its subsets.{\par\medskip}

\begin{Rmk}
There can be sub-{lim-rim} s of a {lim-rim}\ $E$ over $B$ in two ways (or both combined):
Firstly, any subset $E'\subset E$ has the structure of a {lim-rim}\ over $B$,
and secondly for any $B'\subset B$ the set ${^\star} B'$ of the $e\in E$ that satisfy
the ${^\star} $ of `` belongs to $B'$ '' forms a {lim-rim}\ over $B'$. Instead of
talking about sub-{lim-rim} s one may talk about embeddings. Isomorphisms and
automorphisms of {lim-rim} s are defined as expected (as those which respect the
ultrafilter ${\mathcal{L}}$).
\end{Rmk}
{\par\medskip}

\subsection{Confined {Non-Standard Analysis}, Separated and Rectified {Lim-Rim} s}
\begin{Def}
Let ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$ be an infinite cardinality. Given a {non-standard analysis}\ {as per Definition \ref{Def:na}}, let $A$ be a set and ${^\star} x\in{^\star} A$. We say that ${^\star} x$ is {{\em\bf} ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$-confined} or has {{\em\bf} confinement ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$} if there exists a (standard) set $A'\subset A$ of cardinality $\le{\mathfrak{{m}}}$ such that ${^\star} x\in{^\star} A'$. If ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$ is a cardinality such that all {non-standard}\ ${^\star} x$'s in ${^\star} A$ for all sets $A$ are ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$-confined, we say that the {non-standard analysis}\ is {{\em\bf} ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$-confined}, or that it has {{\em\bf} confinement} ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$.
\end{Def}

It is clear that for any infinite cardinality ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$, and any (standard) map $f:A\to B$, $f$ maps {non-standard}\ elements of confinement ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$ to {non-standard}\ elements of confinement ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$ (if ${^\star} x\in{^\star} A'$ where $A'\subset A$ and $|A'|\le{\mathfrak{{m}}}$, then ${^\star} f({^\star} x)\in{^\star} f({^\star} A')$. By Transfer ${^\star} f({^\star} A')={^\star} (f(A'))$ and $|f(A')|\le{\mathfrak{{m}}}$).{\par\medskip}

Therefore if for each set $A$ we define ${^\star} A_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}:=$ the set of ${^\star} x\in{^\star} A$ with confinement ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$, we get a functor $A\mapsto{^\star} A_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}$. That functor is a {non-standard analysis}. Indeed, for finite sets $F$ every {non-standard}\ element is standard, thus ${^\star}$belongs to a standard singleton, hence is of all confinements. Therefore ${^\star} F_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}={^\star} F$; for a product $A\times B$, an $({^\star} x,{^\star} y)\in{^\star} (A\times B)={^\star} A\times{^\star} B$ is ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$-confined if and only if both ${^\star} x$ and ${^\star} y$ are so. Therefore
${^\star} (A\times B)_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}={^\star} A_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}\times{^\star} B_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}$;
and for equalizers the required assertion is clear.{\par\medskip}

We call the {non-standard analysis}\ $A\mapsto{^\star} A_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}$: the {non-standard analysis}\ $A\mapsto{^\star} A$
{{\em\bf} ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$-confined}, or the {{\em\bf} ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$-confinement} of the {non-standard analysis}\ $A\mapsto{^\star} A$.{\par\medskip}

Now suppose a {non-standard analysis}\ is given which has confinement ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$, and let $B$ be some set of cardinality ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$. Suppose we know the {lim-rim}\ $E={^\star} B$ over $B$ that $A$ induces on $B$.{\par\medskip}

It seems evident that we can recover the {non-standard}\ elements ${^\star} A$ of any set (or class) $A$ using that {lim-rim}. Indeed, since the {non-standard analysis}\ has confinement ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$, any {non-standard}\ element ${^\star} x$ of $A$ belongs to a set of the form $f(B)$ for some (standard) $f:B\to A$, hence, by Transfer, is of the form ${^\star} x=f(e)$ for some $e\in E={^\star} B$. We can take the pair $(f,e)$ as a kind of ``coordinates'' for ${^\star} x$, and all we need is to determine when two pairs $(f_1,e_1)$\,\, $(f_2,e_2)$ define the same ${^\star} x$ and how ${^\star} g:{^\star} A\to{^\star} A'$, for some $g:A\to A'$, is expressed using these ``coordinates''. But these characterisations are straightforward, since Transfer must hold. In fact, we use the ``template'' {lim-rim}\ $E$ over $B$ to define the {non-standard}\ elements of any set by, in essence, ``carrying'' them over from $B$ in some analogy with the way tangent vectors may be defined in any smooth manifold by ``carrying'' them over from ${\mathbb{{R}}}^n$.{\par\medskip}

By this way we can start from any {lim-rim}\ $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$ over $B$ and define a $|B|$-confined {non-standard analysis}\, which will be (equivalent to) the {\em $|B|$-confinement} of any {non-standard analysis}\ which induces on $B$ a {lim-rim}\ isomorphic to $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$.{\par\medskip}

Still, we can achieve that goal more ``neatly''.

\begin{Prop}\label{Prop:lrna}
Let $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$ be a {lim-rim}\ over an infinite set (basis) $B$. For any set $X$, let
${^\star} X$ be defined as the ``cylindrical'' ultrapower of $X$ with respect to $B^E$ and ${\mathcal{L}}$, namely, the set $\left( X^{B^E}\right)_c$ of all mappings from $B^E$ to $X$ which depend only on a finite set of coordinates in $B^E$ (that set of coordinates depending on the mapping), factored by the equivalence relation of equivalence modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$. (And the ${^\star}$ of mappings between sets $f:X\to Y$ defined by composing with a representant of ${^\star} x$).

Then: (i) $X\mapsto{^\star} X$ is a $|B|$-confined {non-standard analysis}. It is called: the ($|B|$-confined) {non-standard analysis}\
{{\em\bf} induced by the {lim-rim}}.

(ii) If $X\mapsto{}{{}^\star_0} X$ is a $|B|$-confined {non-standard analysis}\ which induces on $B$ a {lim-rim}\ isomorphic to $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$, then $X\mapsto{}{{}^\star_0} X$ is equivalent to $X\mapsto{^\star} X$ via the two following natural mappings:

${\alpha}={\alpha}_X:{^\star} X\to{}{{}^\star_0} X$: let $\phi:B^E\to X$ be a representant of ${^\star} x\in{^\star} X$. $\phi$ depends only on a finite set of coordinates $e_1,\ldots,e_n$. Hence we may write for $\psi\in B^E$, $\phi(\psi)=f(\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})$,\,\,$f:B^n\to X$. We may assume $E={}{{}^\star_0} B$, and define ${\alpha}({^\star} x):=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f\Big)(e_1,\ldots,e_n)\in{}{{}^\star_0} X$.

${\gamma}={\gamma}_X:{}{{}^\star_0} X\to{^\star} X$: let ${{}^\star_0} x\in{}{{}^\star_0} X$. Since the {non-standard analysis}\ is $|B|$-confined, there is an $f:B\to X$ such that ${{}^\star_0} x\in{}{{}^\star_0} \Big(f(B)\Big)=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f\Big)(E)$. Thus ${{}^\star_0} x=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f\Big)(e)$ for some $e\in E$. Define ${\gamma}({}{{}^\star_0} x)$ as $\psi\in B^E\mapsto f(\psi_e)$ modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$. This does not depend on the choice of $f$.
\end{Prop}

\begin{Prf}
Clearly $X\mapsto{^\star} X$ is a functor, and as in Example \ref{exm:na} one sees that it satisfies (i) and (ii) of Definition \ref{Def:na}. Therefore it is a {non-standard analysis}. Every ${^\star} x\in{^\star} X$, with a representant
$\phi:B^E\to X$ depending on the $n$ coordinates $e_1,\ldots,e_n$,
$\phi(\psi)=f(\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})$,
${^\star}$belongs to $f(B^n)$, of cardinality $\le|B|$. This proves (i).{\par\medskip}

${\gamma}({{}^\star_0} x)$ does not depend on the choice of $f$. Indeed, if
${{}^\star_0} x=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f_1\Big)(e_1)=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f_2\Big)(e_2)$, then $(e_1,e_2)$\,\,${{}^\star_0} $belongs to the set $\{(b_1,b_2)\in B\times B\,|\,f_1(b_1)=f_2(b_2)\}$. This is the ${^\star}$ of a $2$-relation in $B$, and by the way ${^\star}$ is defined for a {lim-rim}, this means that for $\psi\in B^E$,\,\,$(\psi_{e_1},\psi_{e_2})$ is in that set modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$, i.e.\ $f_1(\psi_{e_1})=f_2(\psi_{e_2})$ modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$. This means that the two definitions for ${\gamma}({}{{}^\star_0} x)$ coincide.

Clearly ${\alpha}$ and ${\gamma}$ are natural mappings.

${\alpha}\circ{\gamma}$ is the identity. Indeed, start from some ${{}^\star_0} x\in{}{{}^\star_0} X$.
${^\star} x:={\gamma}({}{{}^\star_0} x)$ is $\psi\in B^E\mapsto f(\psi_e)$ modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$, where
$f:B\to X$ is such that ${{}^\star_0} x=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f\Big)(e)$. Thus $\psi\in B^E\mapsto f(\psi_e)$ is a representant of ${^\star} x$, and ${\alpha}({\gamma}({}{{}^\star_0} x))={\alpha}({^\star} x):=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f\Big)(e)={}{{}^\star_0} x$.

${\gamma}\circ{\alpha}$ is the identity. Indeed, start from some ${^\star} x\in{^\star} X$ represented by
$\phi:B^E\to X$ which depends on the coordinates $e_1,\ldots,e_n$, i.e.\
for $\psi\in B^E$,\,\,$\phi(\psi)=f(\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})$. Then
${{}^\star_0} x:={\alpha}({^\star} x):=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f\Big)(e_1,\ldots,e_n)$. But by the $|B|$-confinement there are $g:B\to X$ and $e\in E$ such that
${{}^\star_0} x=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} g\Big)(e)$. Then $(e,e_1,\ldots,e_n)$\,\,${{}^\star_0} $belongs to the set
$\{(b,b_1,\ldots,b_n)\in B^{n+1}\,|\,g(e)=f(e_1,\ldots,e_n)\}$, meaning that for
$\psi\in B^E$,\,\,$(\psi_e,\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})$ is in that set modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$,
i.e.\ $g(\psi_e)=f(\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})$ modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$. Thus, ${^\star} x$ is represented also by $\psi\mapsto g(\psi_e)$, hence ${^\star} x={\gamma}({}{{}^\star_0} x)={\gamma}({\alpha}({^\star} x))$.
\end{Prf}

\begin{Cor}\label{Cor:lrna}
Let $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$ be a {lim-rim}\ over an infinite $B$. Then TFAE: (i) There exists a {non-standard analysis}\ which induces on $B$ a {lim-rim}\ isomorphic to $E$. (ii) The {$|B|$-confined {non-standard analysis}\ induced by}\ the {lim-rim}\ $E$ induces on $B$ a {lim-rim}\ isomorphic to $E$.

If these hold, we say that the {lim-rim}\ is {{\em\bf} rectified}.

If these hold, one may take as an isomorphism the map ${\gamma}_B:E\to{^\star} B$ (notations as in Prop.\ \ref{Prop:lrna}).

For any $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$,\,\,${\gamma}_B$ can be characterized as mapping $e\in E$ to the projection $\psi\in B^E\mapsto\psi_e$ modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$.
\end{Cor}

\begin{Prf}
If there exists a {non-standard analysis}\ $A\mapsto{}{{}^\star_0} X$ inducing on $B$ a {lim-rim}\ isomorphic to $E$, then, by taking its $|B|$-confinement, we may assume it is $|B|$-confined, and then by Prop.\ \ref{Prop:lrna} it is equivalent to the $|B|$-confined {non-standard analysis}\ induced by $E$, hence the latter too induces on $B$ a {lim-rim}\ isomorphic to $E$.{\par\medskip}

In this case we may take as the isomorphism the mapping ${\gamma}_B$ from Prop.\ \ref{Prop:lrna}.{\par\medskip}

For any $(E.{\mathcal{L}})$, in the definition of ${\gamma}_B$ we identify ${}{{}^\star_0} B=E$ and take
$f={\mathbf 1}_B$ (and ${{}^\star_0} x=e$). Then ${\gamma}_B(e)=(\psi\mapsto\psi_e)$ modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$.
\end{Prf}

\begin{Def}
A {lim-rim}\ $E$ over $B$ is called {{\em\bf} separated} if for $e_1,e_2\in E$, the set
$\{\psi\in B^E\,|\,\psi_{e_1}=\psi_{e_2}\}$ is in ${\mathcal{L}}$ only if $e_1=e_2$.
\end{Def}

\begin{rmk}
For any {lim-rim}, the relation ``$\{\psi\in B^E\,|\,\psi_{e_1}=\psi_{e_2}\}$ is in ${\mathcal{L}}$''
is an equivalence relation in $E$ and factoring $E$ by it gives a separated {lim-rim}.{\par\medskip}
\end{rmk}

The {lim-rim}\ $E$ being separated just says that the map ${\gamma}_B$ mentioned in Cor.\ \ref{Cor:lrna}: $e\mapsto\Big((\psi\mapsto\psi_e)\mod{\mathcal{L}}\Big)$ is one-to-one. Therefore a rectified {lim-rim}\ is separated. (Or alternatively, the fact that the ${^\star}$ of a diagonal is a diagonal means that the {lim-rim}\ that a {non-standard analysis}\ induces on a set $B$ must be separated.){\par\medskip}

For any {lim-rim}\ $E$ over $B$, the {lim-rim}\ of $B$ in the {$|B|$-confined {non-standard analysis}\ induced by}\ it is called the {{\em\bf} rectification} of $E$. Cor.\ \ref{Cor:lrna} can be phrased as saying that $E$ is rectified if and only if it is isomorphic to its rectification, and then as an isomorphism we can take the map
${\gamma}_B:E\to{^\star} B$ mentioned there.{\par\medskip}

\begin{Prop}\label{Prop:ga}
Let $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$ be a {lim-rim}\ over an infinite $B$, and suppose $E$ separated (then ${\gamma}_B$ is injective. notations as above). Then ${\gamma}_B$ is an isomorphism of {lim-rim} s over $B$ from $E$ to ${\gamma}_B(E)\subset{^\star} B$.
\end{Prop}

\begin{Prf}
Since ${\gamma}_B$ is a bijection between $E$ and ${\gamma}_B(E)$, all we need is to prove it preserves the ultrafilters on the cylinder Boolean algebras of $B^E$ and $B^{{\gamma}_B(E)}$ which define the {lim-rim} s.{\par\medskip}

Now, the set (here $h:B^n\to B$ is a function and $0\in B$ is some fixed (standard) element)

prevtext:
is true, where we took the ${^\star}$ of the relation $\in$ between elements and sets. But ${^\star}\{A\}=\{\nu(A)\}$, hence we find that as sets ${^\star} A=\nu(A)$ (i.e. ${^\star} A={{\buildrel{\,\,\wedge}\over{{\nu(A)}}}\!}$). But we shall keep using different notations: ${^\star} A$ where we emphasize the set of ({non-standard}) elements, and $\nu(A)$ when we emphasize the single element.{\par\medskip}

\subsection{Features of the Conventional Approach to {Non-Standard Analysis}}
{non-standard analysis}\ was constructed by its founder, Abraham Robinson
(\cite{Robinson}) as a {non-standard}\ model of part of Set Theory. In his and
following treatments (see several treatises in the bibliography)
\footnote{In another direction, beginning with E.~Nelson \cite{Nelson}, one
constructs a special Set Theory for {non-standard analysis}.}
the idea is to start with a ``big'' structure -- a set $V$, with the restriction to it of the membership relation $\in$, which will be big enough so that usual mathematics could be done in it (should contain, e.g.\ ${\mathbb{{N}}}$ (the natural numbers), ${\mathbb{{R}}}$ (the real numbers), sets of them, sets of these etc.) $V$ is to be provided with a ``mirror'' ``{non-standard}''
structure ${^\star} V$ with a relation ${{^\star}\!\!}\in$, viewed as an ``interpretation'' of the $\in$ of $V$ (Also, ``interpret'' ``$=$'' in $V$ by ``$=$'' in ${^\star} V$), so that

\begin{enumerate}
\item
$V$ is embedded in ${^\star} V$ -- identified with a subset of ${^\star} V$. The members of
$V$ (thus considered as members of ${^\star} V$) are referred to as {\em standard}
(yet by ``{non-standard}'' elements we mean any members of ${^\star} V$).

\item
A {\em Transfer Principle} holds: any (in some constructions one has to say:
``bounded'') first-order logical expression with members of $V$ as constants which is a true sentence when quantifiers are interpreted relative to $V$ will remain a true sentence if (the constants -- members of $V$ -- are replaced by their identified images in ${^\star} V$ and) $\in$ is replaced by ${{^\star}\!\!}\in$ and the quantifiers are interpreted relative to ${^\star} V$. In this sense ${^\star} V$ is a model to the true in $V$ sentences of the first-order theory with $\in$ and all elements of $V$ as constants.

\item
By Transfer, for any standard set $A$, a standard $a\in V$ will be an ${{^\star}\!\!}\in$-member of it if and only if it is a usual member, but in ${^\star} V$\,\,$A$ may have other, {\em{non-standard}} members. The set of all elements of ${^\star} V$ which ${{^\star}\!\!}\in$-belong to $A$ is denoted by ${^\star} A$. Again by Transfer, ${^\star} (A\times B)$ is canonically identified with ${^\star} A\times\,{^\star} B$, thus for relations, functions etc.\ we have the ${^\star}$-relation, ${^\star}$-function etc.\ among members of ${^\star} V$ (which for standard elements coincides with the original relation, function
etc.) When there is no danger of misunderstanding, one often uses the same
symbol (e.g.\ $+$, $<$) for the ${^\star}$-relation etc.\ as for the original.

\item
${^\star} V$ is indeed ``{non-standard}'' -- it contains elements not in $V$, and one has features, usually some kind of ``saturation'' (see below), which will ensure, say, that there is an ${^\star} n\in{^\star} V$ which ${{^\star}\!\!}\in$-belongs to the set ${\mathbb{{N}}}$ of natural numbers, but such that for every standard $m\in N$,\,\,$m\;{{^\star}\!\!}<{^\star} n$ (i.e.\ $(m,{^\star} n)$ ${{^\star}\!\!}\in$-belongs to the graph of $<$). Such ${^\star} n$'s are naturally referred to as
``infinite'' or ``unlimited''
\footnote{In fact, as in footnote \ref{f:i}, for ${\mathbb{{N}}}$ the existence of ``infinite'' members needs only the existence of some not standard members -- one easily proves using Transfer that all ${^\star}$-members of a finite standard $A$ are standard, hence any ${^\star}$-member of ${\mathbb{{N}}}$ which is not standard is automatically bigger than all standard
numbers.}
and by Transfer they have reciprocals in ${^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$, referred to as ``infinitesimal''.
\end{enumerate}

The ``philosophy'' here is to develop the theory from these properties, paying
less attention to the way such ${^\star} V$ is constructed (or proved to exist).
The usual construction is by an ultrapower or a modification of it.
Anyway, one has to have a set $V$ to make the construction, hence only
subsets of it will have {non-standard}\ members.
{\par\medskip}

\subsection{Ultrafilters of {Non-Standard}\ Elements}
Let us be given a {non-standard analysis}, {as per Definition \ref{Def:na}}. For any set $A$, and any
${^\star} x\in{^\star} A$, and for any $S\subset A$, we have ${^\star} S\subset{^\star} A$, thus either
${^\star} x\in{^\star} S$ or ${^\star} x$ is not in ${^\star} S$ $\Leftrightarrow$ it is in the complement
${{^\star}}A\setminus{^\star} S={^\star} (A\setminus S)$. Put otherwise: for any ${\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$-valued predicate
$f:A\to{\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$ we have ${^\star} f:{}{^\star} A\to{^\star}{\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}={\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$ and ${^\star} f({^\star} x)$ is either ${\textbf{True}}$ or ${\textbf{False}}$.{\par\medskip}

Hence any ${^\star} x\in{}{^\star} A$ induces a map ${\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}^A\to{\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$, which is easily seen to be a Boolean-algebra homomorphism, i.e.\ an ultrafilter in $A$.{\par\medskip}

In fact, we may replace ${\{{\textbf{True}},{\textbf{False}}\}}$ by any other finite set $F$, and view the set ${\beta} A$ of the ultrafilters in $A$ as the set of natural mappings between the functor from ${\mathcal{F}}{\mathcal{I}}{\mathcal{N}}$ to ${\mathcal{S}}{\mathcal{E}}{\mathcal{T}}$\,\,$F\mapsto F^A={\text{Hom}}(A,F)$, and the inclusion functor ${\mathcal{F}}{\mathcal{I}}{\mathcal{N}}\to{\mathcal{S}}{\mathcal{E}}{\mathcal{T}}$.{\par\medskip}

Then to a ${^\star} x\in{^\star} A$ corresponds the ultrafilter: the mapping $[f\mapsto{^\star} f({^\star} x)]:{\text{Hom}}(A,F)\to F$. This is clearly a natural mapping between the functors $A\mapsto{^\star} A$ and $A\mapsto{\beta} A$.{\par\medskip}

Note, that although the functor $A\mapsto{\beta} A$ is a canonically defined functor on sets, which maps injections to injections, it does not preserve finite products (hence is not a {non-standard analysis}\ {as per Definition \ref{Def:na}}). The projections $A\times B\to A$ and $A\times B\to B$ define onto mappings ${\beta}(A\times B)\to{\beta} A$ and ${\beta}(A\times B)\to{\beta} B$, hence induce a ${\beta}(A\times B)\to{\beta} A\times{\beta} B$, which is also onto, but is usually not one-to-one. Thus this functor does not satisfy (ii) of Definition \ref{Def:na} (while it satisfies (i)).{\par\medskip}

One may view a {non-standard analysis}\ as a quest to extend sets by adjoining all (or some) possible limits. This in close analogy in spirit to extending a field to its algebraic closure by adjoining all possible roots of algebraic equations. In the latter case one would like to simply define the adjoined elements as labeled by the irreducible polynomial they satisfy, but that is hampered by such facts as the polynomial whose roots are the sums of the roots of two irreducible polynomials being not irreducible.
\footnote{Which may be viewed as the ``reason'' for the existence of several
conjugate roots: the polynomial $d(t)$ whose roots are the differences of the
roots of the irreducible $f(t)$ has a factor $t$ but also other irreducible
factors, testifying to differences $\ne0$.}
The algebraic closure thus contains conjugate elements with the same irreducible polynomial and for any such elements there is an automorphism of the algebraic closure exchanging them.{\par\medskip}

Similarly in our case we would like to label the adjoined ``{non-standard}\ elements'' by
the ultrafilters on the original set. After all, these ultrafilters (and ultrafilters in finite products of sets) give all the possible ways properties (and relations) can conceivably hold or not. But that would not work precisely because the functor ${\beta}$ does not preserve finite products. There is a naturally defined Cartesian product of filters, but the Cartesian product of two ultrafilters ${\mathcal{U}}\in{\beta} A,{\mathcal{V}}\in{\beta} B$ is in general not an ultrafilter -- it is the intersection of all ultrafilters in $A\times B$ that map to $({\mathcal{U}},{\mathcal{V}})$ in the above mapping ${\beta}(A\times B)\to{\beta} A\times{\beta} B$.{\par\medskip}

We too will have a construction (\S\ref{S:car}) where there will be ``conjugate'' {non-standard}\ elements with the same ultrafilter and any such conjugate elements will be exchangeable by an automorphism, provided one has enough General Continuum Hypothesis (GCH), and then, in the same spirit as with algebraic closures, one has uniqueness (for fixed ``basis'' $B$ -- see below) up to isomorphism, and also universality and homogeneity.
{\par\medskip}


\subsection{{Lim-Rim} s -- Local {Non-Standard Analysis}}
Given a {non-standard analysis}, one may focus on a particular set $B$ and try to extract what the {non-standard analysis}\ says about this $B$ (hence about its subsets).{\par\medskip}

The information telling which {non-standard}\ elements satisfy which relations is encoded in the ultrafilters on $B^I$,\,$I$ finite. The {non-standard analysis}\ gives us a natural mapping $({^\star} B)^I\to{\beta}(B^I)$ between these two (contravariant) functors on $I$ from ${\mathcal{F}}{\mathcal{I}}{\mathcal{N}}$ to ${\mathcal{S}}{\mathcal{E}}{\mathcal{T}}$. If for any set $I\in{\mathcal{S}}{\mathcal{E}}{\mathcal{T}}$ we will define ${\beta}_c(A^I)$ as the set of ultrafilters on the {\em cylinder Boolean algebra of $B^I$} (the members of the cylinder Boolean algebra are the subsets of $B^I$ that depend only on a finite number of coordinates. In case $I$ is finite this is just the power set of $B^I$), then any natural $({^\star} B)^I\to{\beta}(B^I)$ on the finite sets $I$ extends in a unique way to a natural $({^\star} B)^I\to{\beta}_c(B^I)$ on all sets $I$. Moreover, we can take $I={^\star} B$ itself and then the image by the natural mapping of any element of $({^\star} B)^I$ will be known if we know the image in ${\beta}_c\left( B^{{}{{^\star}}B}\right)$ of the identity family $\in({^\star} B)^{{^\star} B}$.

\begin{Def}
We say that a set $E$ has the structure of a {{\em\bf}{lim-rim}} over a set
\footnote{we shall usually have $B$ infinite.}
(basis) $B$ if either of the equivalent following is given. (i) An  ultrafilter ${\mathcal{L}}$ on the cylinder Boolean algebra of $B^E$, which will be referred to as the {{\em\bf} defining cylinder ultrafilter} of the {lim-rim}\ (then we shall also speak of the {lim-rim}\ $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$ over $B$). (ii) A natural mapping between the (contravariant) functors on sets $I$: $E^I$ and ${\beta}_c(B^I)$, where the latter denotes the set of ultrafilters in the cylinder Boolean algebra. It will be referred to as the {{\em\bf} defining natural mapping} of the {lim-rim}. (Note that these functors and the natural mapping are defined for any $I$, yet they are determined by giving them for the finite $I$.)
\end{Def}

Here, the defining cylinder ultrafilter ${\mathcal{L}}$ in $B^E$ can be recovered as the image, by the natural mapping, in ${\beta}_c\left( B^E\right)$, of the identity family in $E^E$. On the other hand, if ${\mathcal{L}}$ is given, what it does is deciding, for any (finite) family $\eta\in E^I$ indexed by a finite $I$ (pushing ${\mathcal{L}}$, using the map $B^E\to B^I$ induced by $\eta:I\to E$, to
an ultrafilter in $B^I$) whether relations -- subsets of $B^I$ -- hold or
not, thus transferring such $I$-relations in $B$ (= subsets of $B^I$) into
$I$-relations in $E$, as a {non-standard}\ setting should. This new $I$-relation in $E$ will be referred to as the {\em transfer} or ${^\star}$ of the original $I$-relation in $B$.{\par\medskip}

To put it otherwise: for an $n$-tuple $(e_1,\ldots,e_n)$ of elements of $E$, a
relation $R\subset B^n$\,\,${^\star}$-holds for $(e_1,\ldots,e_n)$ if and only if for $\psi\in B^E$,
$(\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})\in R$ holds modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$.{\par\medskip}

To conclude:{\par\medskip}

\begin{Prop}
Given a {non-standard analysis}\ {as per Definition \ref{Def:na}}, it induces on any set $B$ a {lim-rim}\ $E$ over $B$, where $E={^\star} B$.
\end{Prop}
And as said above, this {lim-rim}\ captures which relations about $B$, or its subsets, are satisfied by $n$-tuples of {non-standard}\ elements $e_1,\ldots,e_n$. We may say that a {lim-rim}\ $E$ over $B$ defines a ``local'' {non-standard analysis}, with $E$ the set of {non-standard}\ elements of $B$, completely satisfactory as a {non-standard analysis}\ as long as one restricts oneself only to $B$ or its subsets.{\par\medskip}

\begin{Rmk}
There can be sub-{lim-rim} s of a {lim-rim}\ $E$ over $B$ in two ways (or both combined):
Firstly, any subset $E'\subset E$ has the structure of a {lim-rim}\ over $B$,
and secondly for any $B'\subset B$ the set ${^\star} B'$ of the $e\in E$ that satisfy
the ${^\star} $ of `` belongs to $B'$ '' forms a {lim-rim}\ over $B'$. Instead of
talking about sub-{lim-rim} s one may talk about embeddings. Isomorphisms and
automorphisms of {lim-rim} s are defined as expected (as those which respect the
ultrafilter ${\mathcal{L}}$).
\end{Rmk}
{\par\medskip}

\subsection{Confined {Non-Standard Analysis}, Separated and Rectified {Lim-Rim} s}
\begin{Def}
Let ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$ be an infinite cardinality. Given a {non-standard analysis}\ {as per Definition \ref{Def:na}}, let $A$ be a set and ${^\star} x\in{^\star} A$. We say that ${^\star} x$ is {{\em\bf} ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$-confined} or has {{\em\bf} confinement ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$} if there exists a (standard) set $A'\subset A$ of cardinality $\le{\mathfrak{{m}}}$ such that ${^\star} x\in{^\star} A'$. If ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$ is a cardinality such that all {non-standard}\ ${^\star} x$'s in ${^\star} A$ for all sets $A$ are ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$-confined, we say that the {non-standard analysis}\ is {{\em\bf} ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$-confined}, or that it has {{\em\bf} confinement} ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$.
\end{Def}

It is clear that for any infinite cardinality ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$, and any (standard) map $f:A\to B$, $f$ maps {non-standard}\ elements of confinement ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$ to {non-standard}\ elements of confinement ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$ (if ${^\star} x\in{^\star} A'$ where $A'\subset A$ and $|A'|\le{\mathfrak{{m}}}$, then ${^\star} f({^\star} x)\in{^\star} f({^\star} A')$. By Transfer ${^\star} f({^\star} A')={^\star} (f(A'))$ and $|f(A')|\le{\mathfrak{{m}}}$).{\par\medskip}

Therefore if for each set $A$ we define ${^\star} A_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}:=$ the set of ${^\star} x\in{^\star} A$ with confinement ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$, we get a functor $A\mapsto{^\star} A_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}$. That functor is a {non-standard analysis}. Indeed, for finite sets $F$ every {non-standard}\ element is standard, thus ${^\star}$belongs to a standard singleton, hence is of all confinements. Therefore ${^\star} F_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}={^\star} F$; for a product $A\times B$, an $({^\star} x,{^\star} y)\in{^\star} (A\times B)={^\star} A\times{^\star} B$ is ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$-confined if and only if both ${^\star} x$ and ${^\star} y$ are so. Therefore
${^\star} (A\times B)_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}={^\star} A_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}\times{^\star} B_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}$;
and for equalizers the required assertion is clear.{\par\medskip}

We call the {non-standard analysis}\ $A\mapsto{^\star} A_{{\mathfrak{{m}}}}$: the {non-standard analysis}\ $A\mapsto{^\star} A$
{{\em\bf} ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$-confined}, or the {{\em\bf} ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$-confinement} of the {non-standard analysis}\ $A\mapsto{^\star} A$.{\par\medskip}

Now suppose a {non-standard analysis}\ is given which has confinement ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$, and let $B$ be some set of cardinality ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$. Suppose we know the {lim-rim}\ $E={^\star} B$ over $B$ that $A$ induces on $B$.{\par\medskip}

It seems evident that we can recover the {non-standard}\ elements ${^\star} A$ of any set (or class) $A$ using that {lim-rim}. Indeed, since the {non-standard analysis}\ has confinement ${\mathfrak{{m}}}$, any {non-standard}\ element ${^\star} x$ of $A$ belongs to a set of the form $f(B)$ for some (standard) $f:B\to A$, hence, by Transfer, is of the form ${^\star} x=f(e)$ for some $e\in E={^\star} B$. We can take the pair $(f,e)$ as a kind of ``coordinates'' for ${^\star} x$, and all we need is to determine when two pairs $(f_1,e_1)$\,\, $(f_2,e_2)$ define the same ${^\star} x$ and how ${^\star} g:{^\star} A\to{^\star} A'$, for some $g:A\to A'$, is expressed using these ``coordinates''. But these characterisations are straightforward, since Transfer must hold. In fact, we use the ``template'' {lim-rim}\ $E$ over $B$ to define the {non-standard}\ elements of any set by, in essence, ``carrying'' them over from $B$ in some analogy with the way tangent vectors may be defined in any smooth manifold by ``carrying'' them over from ${\mathbb{{R}}}^n$.{\par\medskip}

By this way we can start from any {lim-rim}\ $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$ over $B$ and define a $|B|$-confined {non-standard analysis}\, which will be (equivalent to) the {\em $|B|$-confinement} of any {non-standard analysis}\ which induces on $B$ a {lim-rim}\ isomorphic to $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$.{\par\medskip}

Still, we can achieve that goal more ``neatly''.

\begin{Prop}\label{Prop:lrna}
Let $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$ be a {lim-rim}\ over an infinite set (basis) $B$. For any set $X$, let
${^\star} X$ be defined as the ``cylindrical'' ultrapower of $X$ with respect to $B^E$ and ${\mathcal{L}}$, namely, the set $\left( X^{B^E}\right)_c$ of all mappings from $B^E$ to $X$ which depend only on a finite set of coordinates in $B^E$ (that set of coordinates depending on the mapping), factored by the equivalence relation of equivalence modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$. (And the ${^\star}$ of mappings between sets $f:X\to Y$ defined by composing with a representant of ${^\star} x$).

Then: (i) $X\mapsto{^\star} X$ is a $|B|$-confined {non-standard analysis}. It is called: the ($|B|$-confined) {non-standard analysis}\
{{\em\bf} induced by the {lim-rim}}.

(ii) If $X\mapsto{}{{}^\star_0} X$ is a $|B|$-confined {non-standard analysis}\ which induces on $B$ a {lim-rim}\ isomorphic to $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$, then $X\mapsto{}{{}^\star_0} X$ is equivalent to $X\mapsto{^\star} X$ via the two following natural mappings:

${\alpha}={\alpha}_X:{^\star} X\to{}{{}^\star_0} X$: let $\phi:B^E\to X$ be a representant of ${^\star} x\in{^\star} X$. $\phi$ depends only on a finite set of coordinates $e_1,\ldots,e_n$. Hence we may write for $\psi\in B^E$, $\phi(\psi)=f(\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})$,\,\,$f:B^n\to X$. We may assume $E={}{{}^\star_0} B$, and define ${\alpha}({^\star} x):=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f\Big)(e_1,\ldots,e_n)\in{}{{}^\star_0} X$.

${\gamma}={\gamma}_X:{}{{}^\star_0} X\to{^\star} X$: let ${{}^\star_0} x\in{}{{}^\star_0} X$. Since the {non-standard analysis}\ is $|B|$-confined, there is an $f:B\to X$ such that ${{}^\star_0} x\in{}{{}^\star_0} \Big(f(B)\Big)=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f\Big)(E)$. Thus ${{}^\star_0} x=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f\Big)(e)$ for some $e\in E$. Define ${\gamma}({}{{}^\star_0} x)$ as $\psi\in B^E\mapsto f(\psi_e)$ modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$. This does not depend on the choice of $f$.
\end{Prop}

\begin{Prf}
Clearly $X\mapsto{^\star} X$ is a functor, and as in Example \ref{exm:na} one sees that it satisfies (i) and (ii) of Definition \ref{Def:na}. Therefore it is a {non-standard analysis}. Every ${^\star} x\in{^\star} X$, with a representant
$\phi:B^E\to X$ depending on the $n$ coordinates $e_1,\ldots,e_n$,
$\phi(\psi)=f(\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})$,
${^\star}$belongs to $f(B^n)$, of cardinality $\le|B|$. This proves (i).{\par\medskip}

${\gamma}({{}^\star_0} x)$ does not depend on the choice of $f$. Indeed, if
${{}^\star_0} x=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f_1\Big)(e_1)=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f_2\Big)(e_2)$, then $(e_1,e_2)$\,\,${{}^\star_0} $belongs to the set $\{(b_1,b_2)\in B\times B\,|\,f_1(b_1)=f_2(b_2)\}$. This is the ${^\star}$ of a $2$-relation in $B$, and by the way ${^\star}$ is defined for a {lim-rim}, this means that for $\psi\in B^E$,\,\,$(\psi_{e_1},\psi_{e_2})$ is in that set modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$, i.e.\ $f_1(\psi_{e_1})=f_2(\psi_{e_2})$ modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$. This means that the two definitions for ${\gamma}({}{{}^\star_0} x)$ coincide.

Clearly ${\alpha}$ and ${\gamma}$ are natural mappings.

${\alpha}\circ{\gamma}$ is the identity. Indeed, start from some ${{}^\star_0} x\in{}{{}^\star_0} X$.
${^\star} x:={\gamma}({}{{}^\star_0} x)$ is $\psi\in B^E\mapsto f(\psi_e)$ modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$, where
$f:B\to X$ is such that ${{}^\star_0} x=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f\Big)(e)$. Thus $\psi\in B^E\mapsto f(\psi_e)$ is a representant of ${^\star} x$, and ${\alpha}({\gamma}({}{{}^\star_0} x))={\alpha}({^\star} x):=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f\Big)(e)={}{{}^\star_0} x$.

${\gamma}\circ{\alpha}$ is the identity. Indeed, start from some ${^\star} x\in{^\star} X$ represented by
$\phi:B^E\to X$ which depends on the coordinates $e_1,\ldots,e_n$, i.e.\
for $\psi\in B^E$,\,\,$\phi(\psi)=f(\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})$. Then
${{}^\star_0} x:={\alpha}({^\star} x):=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} f\Big)(e_1,\ldots,e_n)$. But by the $|B|$-confinement there are $g:B\to X$ and $e\in E$ such that
${{}^\star_0} x=\Big({}{{}^\star_0} g\Big)(e)$. Then $(e,e_1,\ldots,e_n)$\,\,${{}^\star_0} $belongs to the set
$\{(b,b_1,\ldots,b_n)\in B^{n+1}\,|\,g(e)=f(e_1,\ldots,e_n)\}$, meaning that for
$\psi\in B^E$,\,\,$(\psi_e,\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})$ is in that set modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$,
i.e.\ $g(\psi_e)=f(\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})$ modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$. Thus, ${^\star} x$ is represented also by $\psi\mapsto g(\psi_e)$, hence ${^\star} x={\gamma}({}{{}^\star_0} x)={\gamma}({\alpha}({^\star} x))$.
\end{Prf}

\begin{Cor}\label{Cor:lrna}
Let $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$ be a {lim-rim}\ over an infinite $B$. Then TFAE: (i) There exists a {non-standard analysis}\ which induces on $B$ a {lim-rim}\ isomorphic to $E$. (ii) The {$|B|$-confined {non-standard analysis}\ induced by}\ the {lim-rim}\ $E$ induces on $B$ a {lim-rim}\ isomorphic to $E$.

If these hold, we say that the {lim-rim}\ is {{\em\bf} rectified}.

If these hold, one may take as an isomorphism the map ${\gamma}_B:E\to{^\star} B$ (notations as in Prop.\ \ref{Prop:lrna}).

For any $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$,\,\,${\gamma}_B$ can be characterized as mapping $e\in E$ to the projection $\psi\in B^E\mapsto\psi_e$ modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$.
\end{Cor}

\begin{Prf}
If there exists a {non-standard analysis}\ $A\mapsto{}{{}^\star_0} X$ inducing on $B$ a {lim-rim}\ isomorphic to $E$, then, by taking its $|B|$-confinement, we may assume it is $|B|$-confined, and then by Prop.\ \ref{Prop:lrna} it is equivalent to the $|B|$-confined {non-standard analysis}\ induced by $E$, hence the latter too induces on $B$ a {lim-rim}\ isomorphic to $E$.{\par\medskip}

In this case we may take as the isomorphism the mapping ${\gamma}_B$ from Prop.\ \ref{Prop:lrna}.{\par\medskip}

For any $(E.{\mathcal{L}})$, in the definition of ${\gamma}_B$ we identify ${}{{}^\star_0} B=E$ and take
$f={\mathbf 1}_B$ (and ${{}^\star_0} x=e$). Then ${\gamma}_B(e)=(\psi\mapsto\psi_e)$ modulo ${\mathcal{L}}$.
\end{Prf}

\begin{Def}
A {lim-rim}\ $E$ over $B$ is called {{\em\bf} separated} if for $e_1,e_2\in E$, the set
$\{\psi\in B^E\,|\,\psi_{e_1}=\psi_{e_2}\}$ is in ${\mathcal{L}}$ only if $e_1=e_2$.
\end{Def}

\begin{rmk}
For any {lim-rim}, the relation ``$\{\psi\in B^E\,|\,\psi_{e_1}=\psi_{e_2}\}$ is in ${\mathcal{L}}$''
is an equivalence relation in $E$ and factoring $E$ by it gives a separated {lim-rim}.{\par\medskip}
\end{rmk}

The {lim-rim}\ $E$ being separated just says that the map ${\gamma}_B$ mentioned in Cor.\ \ref{Cor:lrna}: $e\mapsto\Big((\psi\mapsto\psi_e)\mod{\mathcal{L}}\Big)$ is one-to-one. Therefore a rectified {lim-rim}\ is separated. (Or alternatively, the fact that the ${^\star}$ of a diagonal is a diagonal means that the {lim-rim}\ that a {non-standard analysis}\ induces on a set $B$ must be separated.){\par\medskip}

For any {lim-rim}\ $E$ over $B$, the {lim-rim}\ of $B$ in the {$|B|$-confined {non-standard analysis}\ induced by}\ it is called the {{\em\bf} rectification} of $E$. Cor.\ \ref{Cor:lrna} can be phrased as saying that $E$ is rectified if and only if it is isomorphic to its rectification, and then as an isomorphism we can take the map
${\gamma}_B:E\to{^\star} B$ mentioned there.{\par\medskip}

\begin{Prop}\label{Prop:ga}
Let $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$ be a {lim-rim}\ over an infinite $B$, and suppose $E$ separated (then ${\gamma}_B$ is injective. notations as above). Then ${\gamma}_B$ is an isomorphism of {lim-rim} s over $B$ from $E$ to ${\gamma}_B(E)\subset{^\star} B$.
\end{Prop}

\begin{Prf}
Since ${\gamma}_B$ is a bijection between $E$ and ${\gamma}_B(E)$, all we need is to prove it preserves the ultrafilters on the cylinder Boolean algebras of $B^E$ and $B^{{\gamma}_B(E)}$ which define the {lim-rim} s.{\par\medskip}

Now, the set (here $h:B^n\to B$ is a function and $0\in B$ is some fixed (standard) element)

nexttext:
belongs to ${\mathcal{L}}$.
\end{Prf}

\subsection{Exact {Lim-Rim} s}
\label{S:exact}
Abraham Robinson, the founder of {non-standard analysis}\ \cite{Robinson} did not, of course, wish that the {non-standard analysis}\ will be just the trivial ${^\star} A=A$. His requirement that the {non-standard analysis}\ be an {\em enlargement} can be phrased, on the level of {lim-rim} s, as the requirement that for any ultrafilter ${\mathcal{U}}$ on $B$ (or also on $B^I$,\,\,$I$ finite) there will be an element ${^\star} x\in{^\star} B$ (or in $({^\star} B)^I$) which is mapped to ${\mathcal{U}}$ by the natural mapping that defines the {lim-rim}. But one may require slightly more:

\begin{Def}\label{Def:ex}
A {lim-rim}\ $E$ over an infinite $B$ is called {{\em\bf} exact} if for any finite $I$, $J$ and
for any $\xi:I\to J$,\,\,the diagram expressing the naturality of the natural mapping between the (contravariant) functors $\bullet\to E^\bullet$ and ${\beta}(B^\bullet)$ which defines the {lim-rim}, is ``exact'', in the sense that a member of $E^I$ and a member of ${\beta}(B^J)$ which map to the same member of ${\beta}(B^I)$ both come from some same member of $E^J$.{\par\medskip}

Note, that for this to hold it suffices that it holds for inclusions ``adding one element'' $I\to I\cup\{i\}$ \NOT{guaranteeing that the transfer of relations commutes with
projections $B^{I\cup\{i\}}\to B^I$} and for the map $\{1,2\}\to\{1\}$
(the latter guarantees, as easily seen, that the ${^\star}$ of the relation of equality in $B$ will be the relation of equality in $E$ -- i.e.\ that $E$ be separated).
\end{Def}

Note that for $I=\emptyset$ both $E^\emptyset$ and ${\beta}(B^\emptyset)$ are singletons, $\{\emptyset\}$ if you wish, with subsets naturally viewed as the truth-values ${\textbf{True}}=\{\emptyset\},{\textbf{False}}=\emptyset$ which the natural mapping always preserves.{\par\medskip}

If $E$ is exact then, in particular, applying the exactness of the diagram for the map $\emptyset\to\{1\}$ (or $\emptyset\to I$,\,\,$I$ finite) we have that for every ultrafilter ${\mathcal{U}}$ in $B$ there is an element $e\in E$ whose ultrafilter, i.e.\ whose image in the natural mapping $E\to{\beta} B$, is ${\mathcal{U}}$, that is, $e$ ${^\star}$belongs to all members of ${\mathcal{U}}$ (and of course does not ${^\star}$belong to non-members of ${\mathcal{U}}$, which are the complements of members).
\footnote{This does not hold, in general, for {non-standard analysis}\ constructed by an ultrapower
(if the power in the ultrapower is countable, a countable set will have only
$2^{\aleph_0}$ {non-standard}\ members but has $2^{2^{\aleph_0}}$ ultrafilters.)}
If ${\mathcal{U}}$ is fixed (principal) -- is the family of all subsets containing
some $a\in B$ -- than $e$ is unique and is the element of $E$ to be identified with $a$ (i.e.\ $e=\nu(a)$). If ${\mathcal{U}}$ is free (non-principal), however, one proves that (if $E$ is exact) $e$ is never unique and we have ``conjugate'' {non-standard}\ elements with the same ultrafilter which, as we shall see below, will be exchangeable by an automorphism with
a favorable choice of the {lim-rim}.
{\par\medskip}

\begin{rmk}\label{rmk:Ii}
We may express the exactness of the diagram for a map $I\to I\cup\{i\}$ as follows:
For every family $\eta:I\to E$ of elements of $E$, and any ultrafilter ${\mathcal{U}}$
in $B^{I\cup\{i\}}$ which projects on $B^I$ to the ultrafilter pulled-back from ${\mathcal{L}}$ by $\eta$, one can find an element of $E$ as the image of $i$ so that the pull-back of ${\mathcal{L}}$ by the extended $\eta$ will be ${\mathcal{U}}$.{\par\medskip}
\end{rmk}

This implies that for exact {lim-rim} s, ${^\star}$ of relations will commute with projections $B^{I\cup\{i\}}\to B^I$ ($i\notin I$), i.e.\ with applying $\exists$. Of course, for any {lim-rim}, ${^\star}$ of relations commutes with Propositional Calculus operations. Thus in an exact {lim-rim}\ it commutes with all first-order logical operations. And one has a {\em Transfer Principle}: Any true sentence made as a first-order logical combination of relations on $B$ will turn, by transferring each of the argument relations, into a sentence true for $E$.
{\par\medskip}

\begin{Prop}
Any exact {lim-rim}\ $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$ over $B$ is rectified.
\end{Prop}
\begin{Prf}
