\subsection{Exact {Lim-Rim} s}
\label{S:exact}
Abraham Robinson, the founder of {non-standard analysis}\ \cite{Robinson} did not, of course, wish that the {non-standard analysis}\ will be just the trivial ${^\star} A=A$. His requirement that the {non-standard analysis}\ be an {\em enlargement} can be phrased, on the level of {lim-rim} s, as the requirement that for any ultrafilter ${\mathcal{U}}$ on $B$ (or also on $B^I$,\,\,$I$ finite) there will be an element ${^\star} x\in{^\star} B$ (or in $({^\star} B)^I$) which is mapped to ${\mathcal{U}}$ by the natural mapping that defines the {lim-rim}. But one may require slightly more:

\begin{Def}\label{Def:ex}
A {lim-rim}\ $E$ over an infinite $B$ is called {{\em\bf} exact} if for any finite $I$, $J$ and
for any $\xi:I\to J$,\,\,the diagram expressing the naturality of the natural mapping between the (contravariant) functors $\bullet\to E^\bullet$ and ${\beta}(B^\bullet)$ which defines the {lim-rim}, is ``exact'', in the sense that a member of $E^I$ and a member of ${\beta}(B^J)$ which map to the same member of ${\beta}(B^I)$ both come from some same member of $E^J$.{\par\medskip}

Note, that for this to hold it suffices that it holds for inclusions ``adding one element'' $I\to I\cup\{i\}$ \NOT{guaranteeing that the transfer of relations commutes with
projections $B^{I\cup\{i\}}\to B^I$} and for the map $\{1,2\}\to\{1\}$
(the latter guarantees, as easily seen, that the ${^\star}$ of the relation of equality in $B$ will be the relation of equality in $E$ -- i.e.\ that $E$ be separated).
\end{Def}

Note that for $I=\emptyset$ both $E^\emptyset$ and ${\beta}(B^\emptyset)$ are singletons, $\{\emptyset\}$ if you wish, with subsets naturally viewed as the truth-values ${\textbf{True}}=\{\emptyset\},{\textbf{False}}=\emptyset$ which the natural mapping always preserves.{\par\medskip}

If $E$ is exact then, in particular, applying the exactness of the diagram for the map $\emptyset\to\{1\}$ (or $\emptyset\to I$,\,\,$I$ finite) we have that for every ultrafilter ${\mathcal{U}}$ in $B$ there is an element $e\in E$ whose ultrafilter, i.e.\ whose image in the natural mapping $E\to{\beta} B$, is ${\mathcal{U}}$, that is, $e$ ${^\star}$belongs to all members of ${\mathcal{U}}$ (and of course does not ${^\star}$belong to non-members of ${\mathcal{U}}$, which are the complements of members).
\footnote{This does not hold, in general, for {non-standard analysis}\ constructed by an ultrapower
(if the power in the ultrapower is countable, a countable set will have only
$2^{\aleph_0}$ {non-standard}\ members but has $2^{2^{\aleph_0}}$ ultrafilters.)}
If ${\mathcal{U}}$ is fixed (principal) -- is the family of all subsets containing
some $a\in B$ -- than $e$ is unique and is the element of $E$ to be identified with $a$ (i.e.\ $e=\nu(a)$). If ${\mathcal{U}}$ is free (non-principal), however, one proves that (if $E$ is exact) $e$ is never unique and we have ``conjugate'' {non-standard}\ elements with the same ultrafilter which, as we shall see below, will be exchangeable by an automorphism with
a favorable choice of the {lim-rim}.
{\par\medskip}

\begin{rmk}\label{rmk:Ii}
We may express the exactness of the diagram for a map $I\to I\cup\{i\}$ as follows:
For every family $\eta:I\to E$ of elements of $E$, and any ultrafilter ${\mathcal{U}}$
in $B^{I\cup\{i\}}$ which projects on $B^I$ to the ultrafilter pulled-back from ${\mathcal{L}}$ by $\eta$, one can find an element of $E$ as the image of $i$ so that the pull-back of ${\mathcal{L}}$ by the extended $\eta$ will be ${\mathcal{U}}$.{\par\medskip}
\end{rmk}

This implies that for exact {lim-rim} s, ${^\star}$ of relations will commute with projections $B^{I\cup\{i\}}\to B^I$ ($i\notin I$), i.e.\ with applying $\exists$. Of course, for any {lim-rim}, ${^\star}$ of relations commutes with Propositional Calculus operations. Thus in an exact {lim-rim}\ it commutes with all first-order logical operations. And one has a {\em Transfer Principle}: Any true sentence made as a first-order logical combination of relations on $B$ will turn, by transferring each of the argument relations, into a sentence true for $E$.
{\par\medskip}

\begin{Prop}
Any exact {lim-rim}\ $(E,{\mathcal{L}})$ over $B$ is rectified.
\end{Prop}
