and any finite number of $e$'s and sets as in (\ref{eq:psiOmega1}), there is a $\psi$ which belongs to all of them. For the latter, we will be able to find a $\psi_e$ if $(\psi_{e_1},\ldots,\psi_{e_n})$ belongs to the projection $U'$ of $U$ on $B^n=B^{\{i_1,\ldots,i_n\}}$. This projection is, by assumption, in the cylinder ultrafilter pulled-back from ${\mathcal{L}}_\iota$ by the unextended $\eta$. This means that the set of $\psi$ satisfying this is a cylinder in ${\mathcal{L}}_\iota$, as in (\ref{eq:psiOmega2}). Hence we are left with a finite number of conditions of the form (\ref{eq:psiOmega2}), for cylinders in ${\mathcal{L}}_\iota$ which intersect, ${\mathcal{L}}_\iota$ being a cylinder ultrafilter.
\end{Prf}

\begin{Prop}\label{Prop:car}
Let ${\mathfrak{{b}}}$ be an infinite cardinality.

Let us work in a {non-standard analysis}\ with confinement ${\mathfrak{{b}}}$, saturation ${\mathfrak{{b}}}^+$ and saturation
$(2^{\mathfrak{{b}}})^+$ inside (standard) sets of cardinality $\le{\mathfrak{{b}}}$, and in which for $|B|={\mathfrak{{b}}}$ we have $|{}{^\star} B|=2^{2^{\mathfrak{{b}}}}$. Then
\begin{itemize}
\item[(i)]
Let $B$ be a set of cardinality ${\mathfrak{{b}}}$. Then for every internal subset $\mathbf{\beta}\subset{^\star} B$ which contains all standard elements of $B$, and for every ultrafilter ${\mathcal{U}}$ on $B$, $\exists\;{^\star} x\in\mathbf{\beta}$ whose ultrafilter is ${\mathcal{U}}$.

Consequently, $|\mathbf{\beta}|=2^{2^{\mathfrak{{b}}}}$ (recall that $|{^\star}{}B|=2^{2^{\mathfrak{{b}}}}$).
\item[(ii)]
If $\mathbf{\alpha}$ is internal, then either $\mathbf{\alpha}$ is finite or $\exists$ an internal one-one mapping from an internal $\mathbf{\beta}$ as in (i) to ${\alpha}$, hence $|\mathbf{\alpha}|\ge2^{2^{\mathfrak{{b}}}}$.
\item[(iii)]
If $\mathbf{\alpha}$ is ${^\star}$finite (i.e.\ a ${^\star}$member of a standard family of finite
sets) then $|\mathbf{\alpha}|$ is finite or $2^{2^{\mathfrak{{b}}}}$.
\end{itemize}
\end{Prop}

\begin{Prf}
(i) We use $(2^{\mathfrak{{b}}})^+$-saturation (which holds when working inside $B$):
for any finite family of members of ${\mathcal{U}}$\,\,$\exists\;{^\star} x\in\mathbf{\beta}$ belonging
to all of them (indeed a standard one), and by saturation we are done.

(ii) Here we use ${\mathfrak{{b}}}^+$-saturation: If $\mathbf{\alpha}$ is not finite, then for every
finite set $F$ of standard members of $B$\,\,\,$\exists$ an internal set
$\mathbf{\beta}_F\subset{^\star} B$ containing all members of $F$ and an internal one-one mapping
$\mathbf{\beta}_F\to{\alpha}$ (take $\mathbf{\beta}_F=F$), hence by saturation $\exists$ a $\mathbf{\beta}$ suitable for all standard members of $B$.

(iii) Suppose $\mathbf{\alpha}$ not finite. By (ii) $|\mathbf{\alpha}|\ge2^{2^{\mathfrak{{b}}}}$. On the other hand, by ${\mathfrak{{b}}}^+$-confinement $\mathbf{\alpha}$ ${^\star}$belongs to a standard set $S$ of cardinality $\le{\mathfrak{{b}}}$ whose members are finite sets. Then $|\cup S|\le{\mathfrak{{b}}}$, thus
$|{}{^\star}(\cup S)|\le2^{2^{\mathfrak{{b}}}}$, while $\mathbf{\alpha}\subset{}{^\star}(\cup S)$.
\end{Prf}

From Prop.\ \ref{Prop:22b}, Prop.\ \ref{Prop:car} and Prop.\ \ref{Prop:BregB} we get

\begin{Cor}
Let $E$ be a {lim-rim}\ over $B$ as in Prop.\ \ref{Prop:22b}. Let $B'$ be an infinite subset of $B$. Suppose we have the case $2^{2^{|B|}}=\Big(2^{|B|}\Big)^+$ of GCH. Let $E'={^\star} B'\subset E$. Then the {lim-rim}\ $E'$ over $B'$ is {\em the} regular {lim-rim}\ of cardinality $2^{2^{|B|}}$ over $B'$.
\end{Cor}

\section{Iterated {non-standard analysis}}
\subsection{The Embeddings $\nu$ and ${^\star}\nu$}
Fix a {non-standard analysis}\ {as per Definition \ref{Def:na}}. For every set $A$, we have ${^\star} A$, but, of course, ${^\star} A$ being again a set, we have ${^\star}{^\star} A$, also ${^\star}{^\star}{^\star} A$ etc. The {non-standard analysis}\ defines, for every set $A$, an injection $\nu:A\to{^\star} A$ mapping $a\in A\mapsto\nu(a)\in{^\star} A$. Therefore we have (again an injection, by Transfer) ${^\star}\nu:{^\star} A\to{^\star}{^\star} A$. Note that we still have $\nu:{^\star} A\to{^\star}{^\star} A$.{\par\medskip}

Both $\nu$ and ${^\star}\nu$ are injective. Thus both ``embed'' ${^\star} A$ in ${^\star}{^\star} A$. Yet they are highly different, as we shall see.{\par\medskip}

$\nu$, of course, satisfies Transfer. But by Transferring Transfer we find that also ${^\star}\nu$ satisfies a kind of Transfer. One just has to be careful with quantifiers -- on which set to take them.{\par\medskip}

Let us note that
\begin{Prop}
For any (standard) set $A$, and any (standard) $a\in A$, the ${^\star}{^\star}$A-elements $\nu(\nu(a))$ and $({^\star}\nu)(\nu(a))$ are the same.
\end{Prop}
\begin{Prf}
For any map $f:A\to B$, ${^\star} f:{^\star} A\to{^\star} B$ does to the $\nu$ of elements of $A$ the same as $f$ does to the elements. This means ${^\star} f(\nu(a))=\nu(f(a)),\,a\in A$. Now take $B={^\star} A$ and $f:A\to B$ to be $\nu:A\to{^\star} A$.
\end{Prf}
And one easily sees that $a\mapsto\nu(\nu(a))$ and $a\mapsto({^\star}\nu)(\nu(a))$ ``transfer'' relations and functions in the same way.{\par\medskip}

To clarify the relationship between these $\nu$ and ${^\star}\nu$ let us consider, as an example, the case $A={\mathbb{{R}}}$, with its subset ${\mathbb{{N}}}$.{\par\medskip}

\subsection{{Non-Standard Analysis}\ and Iterated {Non-Standard Analysis}\ in ${\mathbb{{R}}}$ and ${\mathbb{{N}}}$}
We place ourself in a {non-standard analysis}\ which is $\aleph_0^+$-saturated, and look at the {non-standard analysis}\ inside ${\mathbb{{R}}}$, in particular inside its subset ${\mathbb{{N}}}$.{\par\medskip}

$\aleph_0^+$-saturation implies that for a descending sequence ${^\star} a_n$, (and an ascending sequence ${^\star} b_n$) of ${^\star}$members of ${\mathbb{{R}}}$ (or any other linearly ordered set), such that ${^\star} a_n>{^\star} b_m\,\forall n,m$  there is a ${^\star}$member ${^\star} c$ of ${\mathbb{{R}}}$ such that ${^\star} a_n>{^\star} c$ (and ${^\star} c>{^\star} b_m$)\,$\forall n,m$. In particular, there are ${^\star}$reals, also ${^\star}$natural numbers, that are bigger than all finite standard numbers. These are sometimes called (positive) {\em infinite} or {\em unlimited}, while a ${^\star}$real whose absolute value is not unlimited will be called {\em limited}. While for any $n\in{\mathbb{{N}}}$ the set $]\leftarrow,n]$ in ${\mathbb{{N}}}$ is finite, therefore all its ${^\star}$membrs are standard, and consequently all ${^\star}$natural numbers are either standard or unlimited, there are ${^\star}$real numbers $>0$ but smaller than any standard positive real. As is well-known, these are called (positive) {\em infinitesimal} ${^\star}$reals (and a positive or negative ${^\star}$real is called infinitesimal if its absolute value is infinitesimal). As is well-known, and easily proved using the completeness of ${\mathbb{{R}}}$ (say, the existence of suprema and infima), for any {\em limited} ${^\star} a\in{^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$ there is a unique standard $\textrm{st}({^\star} a)\in{\mathbb{{R}}}$ so that ${^\star} a-\textrm{st}({^\star} a)$ is infinitesimal. Two ${^\star}$reals whose difference is infinitesimal are called {\em near}.{\par\medskip}

Now, as said above, ${^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$ also has its ${^\star}$members, forming the set ${^\star}{^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$ which may be referred to as the ${^\star}{^\star}$reals. And there is a $\nu:{^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}\to{^\star}{^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$ which maps each ${^\star}$real to the ${^\star}{^\star}$real to be identified with it, and since there is $\nu:{\mathbb{{R}}}\to{^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$, it gives rise to ${^\star}\nu:{^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}\to{^\star}{^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$. As said above, these are two
``embeddings'' of ${^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$ into ${^\star}{^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$.{\par\medskip}

Let's take a look at the set of positive (thus nonzero) infinitesimal ${^\star}$reals. Note that, by the above, for any ascending (resp.\ descending) sequence of them there is a positive infinitesimal further bigger (resp. smaller) than all of them. The set of infinitesimals is external -- if it were internal it would have a ${^\star}$supremum which is impossible. It has ${^\star}$members, the ${^\star}$infinitesimals -- thay are ${^\star}{^\star}$reals. In particular, since for any set $A$\,\,$\nu$ maps $A$ into ${^\star} A$, $\nu$ of infinitesimals are ${^\star}$infinitesimals.{\par\medskip}

Now, since the positive infinitesimals are the positive ${^\star}$reals that are smaller than $\nu(r)$ for all reals $r>0$, we have by Transfer: the positive ${^\star}$infinitesimals are the positive ${^\star}{^\star}$reals smaller than ${^\star}\nu({^\star} r)$ for all ${^\star}$reals ${^\star} r>0$. But note that we can take here as ${^\star} r$ a positive infinitesimal! Thus we have:{\par\medskip}

All positive ${^\star}$infinitesimals, which include the $\nu$ of positive infinitesimals, are smaller than all ${^\star}\nu$ of positive infinitesimals!{\par\medskip}

