We had the (equivalence) relation in ${^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$ of ``being near'', i.e.\ having an infinitesimal difference. In fact, it is an intersection $\cap_n{^\star} U_n$ of the ${^\star}$'s of a decreasing sequence of standard relations $U_n\subset{\mathbb{{R}}}\times{\mathbb{{R}}}$, in this case a basis to the uniformity in ${\mathbb{{R}}}$. We had: the equivalence class of a limited ${^\star} a\in{^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$ contains a unique standard $\nu(\textrm{st}({^\star} a))$,\,\,$\textrm{st}({^\star} a)$ called the {\em standard part} of ${^\star} a$. Moving from such a relation to a relation in ${^\star}{^\star}{\mathbb{{R}}}$, we have two options:{\par\medskip}

