Indeed, $(\star)$ holds if and only if ${^\star} b$ satisfies the ${^\star}$ of the property of $b\in B$: ``$\nu(b)$ is in the relation $R$ with ${^\star} a$''. By Transferring, this means that it satisfies: ``${^\star}\nu({^\star} b)$ is in the relation $R$ with $\nu({^\star} a)$''.
\end{Prf}
{{\em\bf} Some examples}:
\begin{itemize}
\item Take $R$ as the relation of {\em inequality} in $A$. Thus to have ${^\star}\nu({^\star} b)\ne\nu({^\star} a)$,\,\,${^\star} b$ must ${^\star}$beloing to the set of $b\in A$ unequal to ${^\star} a$, this set being the whole $A$ unless ${^\star} a$ is standard. For standard ${^\star} a=\nu(a),\,a\in A$,\,\,${^\star}\nu({^\star} b)$ can equal $\nu({^\star} a)={^\star}\nu(\nu(a))$ only if ${^\star} b=\nu(a)$. Therefore:{\par\medskip}

The ${^\star}\nu$ of a ${^\star}$A-member can equal the $\nu$ of a ${^\star}$A-member only if both are standard and equal.{\par\medskip}

\item Let $A$ be partially ordered, and take as $R$ the relation $a\ge b$. $(\star)$ says that ${^\star} b$ ${^\star}$belongs to the cone of the standard minorants of $a$. Thus if ${^\star} a$ is ``infinite'' in the sense of majorizing all standard elements, then the latter cone is everything so we always have ${^\star}\nu({^\star} b)\le\nu({^\star} a)$ (similarly to what we saw in ${\mathbb{{R}}}$ and ${\mathbb{{N}}}$ in the previous subsection).{\par\medskip}

\item Let $A$ be a (standard) set and $B$ a set of subsets of $A$, with the relation $a\in b$. Then $\nu({^\star} a)\in{^\star}\nu({^\star} b)$ (here we identify a ${^\star}$set with its scope -- see \S\ref{S:NAFco}) if and only if ${^\star} b$ is a ${^\star}$member of the family of standard sets ${^\star}$containing ${^\star} a$, and ${^\star}\nu({^\star} a)\in\nu(b)$ if and only if ${^\star} a$ is a ${^\star}$member of the set of standard members of ${^\star} b$.{\par\medskip}

\item Let $X$ be a Banach (resp.\ Hilbert) space. Then on ${^\star} X$ there is a ${^\star} {\mathbb{{R}}}$-valued norm (resp.\ inner product and norm). In a well-known construction, one takes the space of elements of ${^\star} X$ with {\em limited} norm and quotient it by the subspace of infinitesimal vectors (i.e.\ those with infinitesimal norm), (and denote equivalence classes modulo the infinitesimals by $[\,\,]$), to get an ordinary Banach (resp.\ Hilbert) space, called the {\em {non-standard}\ hull} of $X$. Denote it by ${\mathcal{H}}(X)$. It is complete, provided we have $\aleph_0^+$-saturation.
\footnote{Indeed, Suppose $[{^\star} x_n]$ is a Cauchy sequence in ${\mathcal{H}}(X)$. For any $m\in{\mathbb{{N}}}$, choose a ball $B_m=\{{^\star} x\in{^\star} X\,|\,\|{^\star} x-{^\star} a\|<1/m\}$ of radius $1/m$ which contains all ${^\star} x_n$ from some $n$ on. The $B_m$ are internal sets and any finite number of them intersect (since they all contains all ${^\star} x_n$ from some $n$ onward). By $\aleph_0^+$-Saturation they all intersect, and if ${^\star} x_0$ is a member of the intersection, then clearly $[{^\star} x_n]\to[{^\star} x_0]$.}
The $\nu:H\to{^\star} H$, followed by the factoring by the infinitesimals, defines a (norm-preserving) embedding of $X$ into ${\mathcal{H}}(X)$.{\par\medskip}

(In general, this embedding is not onto -- ${\mathcal{H}}(X)$ has much more elements that $X$. For example, if $X=\ell^p$ then ${\mathcal{H}}(X)$ consists of equivalence classes of ``sequences'' defined on ${^\star}{\mathbb{{N}}}$, and a sequence may have infinitesimal entries but finite nonzero norm, or can be supported on unlimited ${^\star}$numbers, and then it is not in the image of $X$.){\par\medskip}

As for ${^\star}{^\star} X$, we have here, similarly to what we saw in ${\mathbb{{R}}}$, the
${^\star}$infinitesimal vectors -- vectors with ${^\star}$infinitesimal norm, which are part of the ${^\star}{^\star}$vactors with ``weakly infinitesimal'' norm. Call the latter ``weakly infinitesimal'' ${^\star}{^\star}$vactors. Factoring the space of ${^\star}{^\star}$vactors whose norm is bounded by a ($\nu\circ\nu$ of a) standard number by the ``weakly infinitesimal'' ones one again gets an ordinary Banach space (resp.\ Hilbert space) ${\mathcal{H}}^{(2)}(X)$.{\par\medskip}

Now, $\nu,{^\star}\nu:{^\star} X\to{^\star}{^\star} X$ will define two embeddings of ${\mathcal{H}}(X)$ into ${\mathcal{H}}^{(2)}(X)$, which by abuse of language we also refer to as $\nu$ and ${^\star}\nu$.{\par\medskip}

To see an example of what Prop.\ \ref{Prop:nunustar} would say here, take $X$ to be a Hilbert space. Suppose $[{^\star} a]\in{\mathcal{H}}(X)$ and $[{^\star} b]$ belong to the orthogonal complement of $X$ in ${\mathcal{H}}(X)$. Then for any (standard) ${\varepsilon}>0$ the set of standard vectors $b$ with $|<b,{^\star} a>|<{\varepsilon}$ is everything. So by Prop.\ \ref{Prop:nunustar} $|<{^\star}\nu({^\star} b),\nu({^\star} a)>|<{\varepsilon}$. Consequently:{\par\medskip}

If $[{^\star} a]\in{\mathcal{H}}(X)$ and $[{^\star} b]$ belong to the orthogonal complement of $X$ in ${\mathcal{H}}(X)$ then $[{^\star}\nu({^\star} b)]$ is always orthogonal to $[\nu({^\star} a)]$. (In particular, $[{^\star}\nu({^\star} b)]$ is orthogonal to $[\nu({^\star} b)]$.)
\end{itemize}
\bigskip

Another application of Prop.\ \ref{Prop:nunustar},
\begin{Prop}
Assume the {non-standard analysis}\ is $\aleph_0^+$-saturated.

Let $A$ be linearly ordered. (i.e.\ every $a,b\in A$ satisfy $a\ge b$ or $b\ge a$). Then a necessary and sufficient condition for $A$ to be well-ordered is that{\par\medskip}

For every ${^\star} a\in{^\star} A$,\,\,${^\star}\nu({^\star} a)\le\nu({^\star} a)$.
\end{Prop}
\begin{Prf}
Suppose $A$ is well-ordered and ${^\star} a\in{^\star} A$. Let $c$ be the least (standard) element of $A$ satisfying $c>{^\star} a$ --
if there is no $c$ with $c>{^\star} a$ denote $c=\infty$. Then ${^\star} a$ ${^\star}$belongs to the set of standard elements $<c$, which is the set of standard elements $\le{^\star} a$, hence by Prop.\ \ref{Prop:nunustar} ${^\star}\nu({^\star} a)\le\nu({^\star} a)$.{\par\medskip}

Suppose now that $A$ is not well-ordered, thus contains a strictly descending sequence $(a_n)$. By $\aleph_0^+$-saturation, there is a ${^\star} a\in{^\star}\{a_n\}$ smaller than all the $a_n$. The set of (standard) members of
$\{a_n\}$ that are $>{^\star} a$ is the whole $\{a_n\}$, to which ${^\star} a$ certainly ${^\star}$belongs. Hence, by
Prop.\ \ref{Prop:nunustar}, ${^\star}\nu({^\star} a)>\nu({^\star} a)$ and the condition is not satisfied.
\end{Prf}

